remove it from our legs, one leg at a time, and then we had to be
naked and then the water would be sprayed from outside through a
water hose, and some would get soaked, some would miss the water.
And then we would use the clothes to dry the water.  It was so
miserable because we would -- had been treated like the cattle
while we were sprayed the water on.
When we asked for water, of course we had to ask them for
permission.  Otherwise we would never be given such water to
drink.
Q. You said you took off your shorts to dry the water.  What was
the purpose of doing so?
A. We only used them to dry the floor so that we could -- when
the floor dried then we could lie down, because the water floods
the floors and we had to dry it to make sure that it's dry.
Q. So the purpose of removing your shorts was to dry the floor so
that you could sleep on it.  Is that correct?
A. That is correct, Mr. President.
Q. How often were you sprayed the water on like this?
A. Once every week or maybe once every fortnight.  I don't
remember; you know, it has been 30 years or more already, but I
know that every time we had a bath, everyone had to be naked.  It
was like hell.
Everyone would look the same and sometimes they mocked at us.
They said that you guys look small physically but your thing was
not that small.  I'm sorry to say that, but we would laugh by
mocking on some other things, private things.
Q. When you were detained, besides being removed from the
shackles to be interrogated, were you released to do exercises,
for example, every now and then or were you never allowed to do
that?
A. I don't remember it.  I think we were never allowed to do
exercise in the room or maybe we were allowed to do so.  I am not
sure because it has been so long already.
Q. When you were taken to be interrogated, how was the process
carried out?
A. Every time I was taken to be interrogated, they would handcuff
me and walked to the compound of the prison to Building A.  I
think the previous trace of the building vanished over time and I
think I could never take any visitors to the same original
location as it already altered.
Q. When you were removed from shackles, then you would be
handcuffed before you would be walked to be interrogated.  Can
you please tell us how this process would be carried out?
A. I was walked to the interrogation room into the house.  We
walked to upstairs.
Q. No, I'm talking about the time when you were in the room and
were shackled, and then you were shackled and attached to other
people, other detainees.  And before you were taken to the
interrogation room, would you be removed from the shackles and
then walked outside of your room before you would be re-shackled
again and walked to the interrogation room?
A. They removed the shackles from the long bar.  The shackles
were removed then they cuffed -- they put the cuffs on me again
and then they walked to the outside area of the room, or the
prison.
Q. Were you blindfolded when you were being walked away?
A. Of course, I was blindfolded while I was being walked away.
Q. Could you please tell us about the moment when you were put
into the room for interrogation?  How were you treated by the
guards?
A. They treated us -- they used derogatory language to me and
they shackled me by my ankles -- the long bar of shackles which
was about half a metre -- and then they locked the chain and then
they closed all the windows and doors.  No, I think the windows
would be left open because there were metal bars.  I could see
Building A or B clearly.
After I was shackled and they removed the handcuffs and removed
the blindfold, and then they started to beat me to answer when I
entered CIA and KGB.  I told them that I did not know anything
about it and I could not answer anything about CIA and KGB.
I kept repeating my response and they kept beating me and, of
course, if we did not respond or answer to satisfy their request,
then we would be beaten severely.
Q. During the time when you were interrogated, you would be
shackled and then you would be asked to sit on the floor while
your handcuffs would be removed along with the blindfold before
you would be interrogated.  In case you did not respond to what
they wanted to get the confession from you, then you would be
beaten with a stick.  Do I understand you correctly?
A. They removed the blindfold and handcuffs.  They put me to lie
face down and then they started to beat me until they had enough,
and then they kept asking me when I entered CIA and KGB and who
introduced me into the agents.  And I did not know how to respond
to them because the person who worked honestly and worked the
best to serve Angkar and never been involved in such
organization, how could I respond to them that I introduced
anyone into the CIA, even myself.  I did not know what CIA was.
Q. You said you were shackled and put face down.  I find it
difficult to understand because if you talk about the shackle,
then you could sit up.  And how could you be put face down and
then if you were shackled before that, you could not sit up
because it was a wooden kind of shackles.  Then you put your legs
-- or your legs were put into the shackle then you would not be
able to lie face down on the floor.
Or were you put to lie face down on the floor and tortured before
they removed the shackles, and then -- or what?  Could you please
clarify it to me or to the Court?
A. It was not a wooden shackle, Mr. President.  It was a metal
bar, long bar, designed to only put on one individual detainee.
After having that long metal bar attached to my legs and my
ankles, then they locked both ends and then they put me to lie
face down in order for the interrogator to be able to beat me on
my back and I could put my face down.
Q. Were you taken to be interrogated immediately when you were
sent during the first night at S-21 or were you kept a few days;
only later that they would take you to be interrogated?
A. Mr. President, I was detained for quite a long time.  I think
it was until May or June 1977 so I had been detained for four or
five months before I was interrogated and tortured.  And as I
stated earlier, then a guy came and asking for anyone who could
paint.
Q. Can you try to recall the S-21 staff who took you for
interrogation and torture?  How many times were you taken and
what about the types of torture?
A. Mr. President, when -- for every times they interrogated and
tortured me, they did not use or change the method.  First, they
used a rattan stick or a whip to beat me up.  They beat me up
with the stick or the whip for the two sessions.  So from 7 until
12 or 1 p.m. in the morning, then I was allowed to eat and in the
afternoon, they only stopped after 6 or 7 p.m. when I was taken
back to the room.  After they beat me up, they did not take me to
the common room.  They took me to the individual cell.  So every
time after the interrogation and the torture, I was taken to the
ground floor -- to the individual cell.  And for the mealtime,
then we were fed with a bowl of food.
Q. So in summary, you were detained in two different rooms.
First, you were in the common room and about five months later,
when they started to interrogate and torture you by using the
stick, then you were detained in an individual cell.  Is that
correct?
A. Mr. President, that is correct.
Q. Was your torture in a different method; for example, by
electrocution?
A. Yes, Mr. President.
One day after they beat me down -- they beat me up, they walked
me to Building D and there was a power outlet on the wall and
then they used an electrical wire to electrocute me.  I felt
unconscious and later on they used the water to pour on my face
and I became unconscious again.  I did not know the voltage of
that electricity, but once they started it, I felt unconscious
immediately.  That was done in Building D.
Q. I already asked you and you said that you did not know if you
committed any offence so when you were detained in the prison,
was there any decision by a trial committee to punish or sentence
you -- for example, in a form of a trial in a similar form of
this Chamber -- during your detention there?
A. Mr. President, no, there was no judgment; no order from
anybody.  We were just detained.  And one day after they
exhausted by beating me up, then they walked me back into the
room and while at the path walking to our Building D -- there was
no concrete path there at the time  -- and at that juncture, I
was beaten up again.  And another person came and said, "Don't
beat him up today because Brother instructed so.  Keep him
alive."
Because there were a lot of wounds on my back, I felt so painful,
but because they beat me up so I had to lie down on my back.
However, Him Huy used a stick to push under my back and a lot of
gravels went inside the wound on my back so because it was so
painful, then I had to turn myself again for them to beat me up
on the back.
Q. When did they decide to use you as a painter?
A. One day, I was taken from that individual cell to the upper
floor for treatment.  Actually, there was no medicine at all.
There was a bowl of saltwater and they just poured that saltwater
on my back and it was so, so painful because of my open wounds
and the salt.  You could see when you used the salt on the frog,
you could see the effects and you could imagine how painful it
was when they pour the water -- the saltwater on my back.  And
indeed, finally the wounds recovered from the saltwater.
Sometimes, I was given a rabbit pellet tablet.  It was so
miserable.
Q. And now to the scars from the beating; do you still have the
scars or are they completely gone?
A. The wounds recovered, but the scars are everywhere on my back,
on my shoulders.  They were the scars from being whipped or
beaten.  Sometimes, there were five of them beating me up at the
same time.
Q. Can we see the scars on your back?

A. Mr. President, towards the later '77, because in early 1978 I

I think I started painting the portrait in late '77 or early '78

asked me, "How long did it take to make that portrait?  And the

I would like to seek your permission to show the portrait of Pol

This is my response, Your Honour.
Q. During the time that you were released to work by doing the
painting, where did you paint and who else worked with you in
that location?
A. Mr. President, yes, I myself, Bou Meng; Vann Nath too; Im
Chan, the wood sculptor and the wax moulder, another wax moulder;
so that's all.  And we worked in Building E.  Building E is the
building in the middle of the compound.  I think that is used as
the reception area for the guests who come to visit the museum.
Q. What about the food ration after you were chosen to work as a
painter?  Was the food ration the same as those given to the
prisoners?
A. Mr. President, the food ration was better than previously, so
it was from the thin gruel to rice and we had sufficient soup.
So the prison guard carried the soup to deliver it to us and we
shared among ourselves.
Q. During the time you were selected to work as a painter, where
were you allowed to sleep at night?
A. After I painted and when it was time to sleep, it was at the
generator's room.  It was behind Building E.  At that time there
was a generator there, so when the electricity was cut off, then
they started the generator and we slept in that generator's room.
Q. Were you cuffed or shackled in that room or were you locked
from outside?
A. I was allowed to sleep in that room but I was not cuffed or
shackled, so there was seven of us -- Oeng Bech, Vann Nath, Im
Chan, Pha Tha Chan, Ruy Makong.  There were seven of us -- and
Chum Mey.  I requested to see the photo: Pha Tha Chan, Bou Meng,
Vann Nath, Im Chan, Ruy Makong and Chum Mey.  And now only Chum
Mey, Vann Nath and Bou Meng are alive.  The other four died.
MS. STUDZINSKY:

BY MR. PRESIDENT:
Q. During the times you were asked to do the painting, did you
meet the accused, Kaing Guek Eav, alias Duch?
A. Mr. President, Your Honours, at that time Mr. Kaing Guek Eav,
alias Duch, sat next to me watching me painting the portrait of
Brother Number One, Pol Pot, and he ordered me, "You should
adjust the throat.  It's not a tumour, it's just fat."  So as can
be seen from this photo which was taken of the portraits that I
painted, so you could see that the throat was slimmer.
Q. Did he come to visit you often to see you painting?  And if he
came, during the day or nighttime?
A. He came often during the daytime and he wore shorts and a
short-sleeved shirt.  So he came in, he sat with his one leg
across and watching me drawing, for example, another portrait of
the head of Ho Chi Minh on the body of a dog.  It was like a
cartoon which they -- it was like a sketch of the sea with a
flat, windy situation, et cetera and et cetera.
Q. Did you notice his character and behaviour during the time
that he watched you making the painting or the portrait?
A. Mr. President, he did not really beat me up, however, one day
I didn't know what I did wrong.  He asked me and Im Chan to beat
each other up.  So we were given a piece of black plastic tube to
hit, to beat each other, and he sat there watching us beating
each other up.  After a while he ordered us to stop.
But if I could make a very lifelike portrait, he would look at it
carefully and I think I lost some of the portraits.
Q. The question is, did you observe his facial expression or his
behaviour; that is the behaviour of the accused, Kaing Guek Eav,
alias Duch, during the time that he went to watch you painting?
Was he a person full of joy or full of sorrow?  Did you notice
that?
A. Mr. President, his facial expression was normal.  If he needed
to laugh, he laughed.  Sometimes he smiled.  I could see him
through his face but I could not judge his feeling or emotion,
and that's the word I was asked especially by a journalist, and I
always tell them, "I know his face but I don't know his feeling".
He was close to me, observing me painting.  Sometimes he gave me
cigarettes to smoke.
Q. Did he ever beat you up personally?
A. No, but he ordered me to beat up with Im Chan.  I was not
happy with that.  He did not treat me like a human being.
Q. Did you ever see him going from one building to the next
within the compound of the prison; for example, from Building A
to B to C, or did he only enter the compound and only come to the
place where you worked?
A. Mr. President, I did not see him walking along each building
because when he entered his main focus was on the portrait of
Brother Number One, Pol Pot.  I only saw him coming to my
workshop.  I did not see him going anywhere else.
Q. So besides him, besides you yourself, did you see him
torturing or beating up other prisoners?
A. Mr. President, let me go back a little bit.
One day there was a Vietnamese citizen.  He boasted that he could
make a wax mould and then he was ordered to show his skill.  So
he was tested and Duch saw that he could not do it.  Then he
ordered the interrogators to kick him like kick a ball because,
from what I understood, he was angry that that person lied to
him.  And I did not know what happened to that Vietnamese person.
Probably he was taken out.
Q. Did he himself order the guards or his subordinates to torture
that person?  And if he did order, can you recall his exact
words; that is, the words that Duch used to order his
subordinates to torture that Vietnamese person?
A. Mr. President, I forget some parts.  I am not sure.  I think
probably he signalled his guards to beat that Vietnamese person.
And the Vietnamese person was taken away from the workshop where
I worked.  So there were woodcrafters; there was a painter and
another artist.  We worked in the same workshop.
Q. You saw the guards beating up that person who boasted about
his skill.  Was the beating taking place within the workshop
vicinity in Building E or was he taken out and beaten up outsides
that area?
A. Mr. President, at that time the three or four of them kicked
that Vietnamese person and beat him up and walked him away.  I
did not hear his order.  So when those guards beat the Vietnamese
person up, Duch had already left.
Q. So during the time you were asked to work as a painter, how
many portraits did you paint and whose portraits were they?
A. There were four portraits of Pol Pot.  However, there was
another portrait in 1981.  There was a German group to make a
film on that portrait, so I showed the portrait to the person and
then I used paint to make a cross sign on that person to express
my hatred of that person, and that was filmed by the German
group.
Q. You said that you painted various other paintings or
portraits; for example, a painting of a dog with the Ho Hi Minh
head on it.  But for Pol Pot portraits you only made four
portraits?
A. That is correct, Mr. President.
Q. So besides the portraits of Brother Number One, Pol Pot, did
you make any other painting or portrait?
A. Mr., President, yes, I painted Hua Guofeng, Mao Zhedong in
large canvas as well, so the canvas was as big as the canvas for
Pol Pot's portrait.
Q. When you did your painting or portrait, did you do it
individually or together with Vann Nath?  That is, Vann Nath was
painting his own painting or portrait and you yourself had a
separate painting or portrait?
A. Mr. President, at that time he did not have a skill of
painting black and white portraits so I mixed the black and white
painting by myself with one litre of gasoline to burn it and the
smoke would go into that painting and then I mixed it.  And Vann
Nath did not have this skill.
Q. So it means that your painting was separate from him because
one was colour and one was black and white.  Is that correct?
A. Yes, that is correct.
Q. You talked about the portrait of Pol Pot.  This is one of the
portraits of other people that you painted.  Is that correct?
A. Yes, Mr. President, that is correct.

They gathered us to move from the compound in one long straight
line without stepping anywhere off the line or we would be shot.

leaving on the 7th of January 1979; is that correct?
A. Mr. President, it's correct, we left at night in the late
evening at about 6 to 7 p.m.

A. After we were blindfolded and sent to the upper upstairs I
have never known or seen my wife.  But at one moment when I was
painting the portrait of Pol Pot, Him Huy was outside of the
window and told me that, "Your wife was working in the rice
field," and then I told myself -- I thought that probably she
would be kept there to be killed, but I did not tell anybody
because I only were thinking alone.  Because I was also a farmer
and Duch once said that people could be used as fertilizer for
rice field or rice farming and that's why I had to be very
careful and I had to work so hard to concentrate on my work and
it took me three months to finish one portrait.
Q. Have you ever learned anything about the fate of your wife or
what happened to her?
A. I don't know what happened to her, whether she would be
tortured.  We were parted since we were taken into that common
room.  Until now we have never seen each other and I never know
what happened to her.
Q. Do you think that she would be killed at S-21, or what else?
A. Your question reminds me the question that I would like to ask
to Mr. Kaing Guek Eav, I want to know whether he asked his
subordinates to smash my wife at S-21 or at Choeung Ek so that I
could collect the ashes or remains so that I can make her soul
rest in peace.

A. I have the photo with me.  If you would wish me to present,

A. This photo was taken during the time we were sent into S-21
because her photo was taken first, followed by me.  You can see
her ID on the photo.

would like to put
further questions concerning the time when you were detained and

observation and recollection, could you please tell the Court
about those events?

painting a portrait of Pol Pot, I could see through the window
the sending of Vietnamese soldiers and the Khmer Rouge soldiers
who were sent en masse into the compound.  I did not actually
witness the torture, but I heard the screams; people crying for
help all around the compound.  I did not see the tortures
directly, but I did hear people crying for help.
Q. When you were detained in the common room, did you see dead
body of other detainees in the room and if you saw them, did you
see them often?
A. Mr. President, I saw a dead body who was lying head to head
with me.  He was with dark complexion, a small person.  He was
taller than me.  He was about the same age as me.  If he would
live, now he would be 67, 68.  A young guard stamped on his chest
and he coughed with blood and he was lying dead there inside the
common room.  At night, he would be taken to be buried in the
compound not far from that.
Q. So how long was it -- I mean, the interval between the time
when the person died and the time when he was buried?
A. I noticed that he was dead in the daytime and then late at
night -- I can't remember when, but it was at night that the
person disappeared and would be buried.  I don't know where he
would be buried or discarded because I was still shackled and I
didn't know more about something outside.
Q. You were detained and shackled for a long period of time
before you were let out to be a painter.  And have you noticed
the people who were sent in and shackled along with you in the
same room would be taken out and disappeared or had they returned
or have you noticed that?
A. I'm talking before the God, the Buddha.  I'm talking the
truth.  People would be put into the trucks and carried away and
they never returned.  And after being interrogated, I would be
kept downstairs and I did not know much about the fate of those
people, but when I was in the common room, people who would be
taken away would never come back so they just disappeared.
Q. What about the other situation, for example, when a detainee
was so weak that he would be carried to the truck or to the other
location?  Had you seen such scenes?
A. I did witness the very thin person who were tied to his legs
and arms, and a stick would be put to -- and then carried by two
people.  He was carried like a pig, like people would be carrying
a pig, and he was passing the place where I was painting, and the
guard banged the door shut in order not to let me see them
carrying that very sick and thin detainee.  I did not know where
he was up to.
Q. Were they carrying the dead body or a person who's still
alive?
A. He was not yet dead.  He was still breathing and then he would
be carried onto the truck waiting outside the prison.  We could
hear the sound of the truck coming in and out all day long.
Q. I think you should have known about this, about the trucks
that came and take people away all night.  Can you tell us
whether the trucks only came during the night or during the
daytime, or detainees would be taken by the trucks at any time
from S-21?  I mean, those people who would be taken away and
would never return.
A. I was in the common cell or common room.  After being
interrogated, I was put in the cell and I could hear the sound of
the trucks.  I never saw the trucks; just heard the sound, the
noise.  I did not know or see the detainees.  I only saw him once
when I was painting the portrait of Pol Pot while they were
carrying him, passing me.
Q. So was it at night or during the daytime?  I'm asking this
because after hearing testimony we have received two different
kinds of information, especially concerning the transportation of
detainees to Choeung Ek, because the information we obtained so
far is that detainees would only be sent during the night.
Another thing is that I don't know whether you're confused among
two of you.  One witness who testified said that during the time
he was detained at the location from the morning until 12 p.m. he
would not be able to sleep because he wait until 12 p.m. passed
so that he knew that no people would be carried away to be killed
after that.  So that's why I would like you to clarify whether
prisoners would be taken at night or in the daytime, especially
regarding the person who was very sick and would be carried away
by two people with a stick.  Was it done during the day or at
night?
A. At that time I did not see at night, of course, but I saw it
during the daytime.  It was about 9 or 10 a.m.; I think more or
less at about nine, between 9 and 10 a.m.
Q. Normally when the trucks came, were the trucks driven to
Building E or just they were parked right in front of the
entrance; close to Building B or C, for example?
A. Mr. President, regarding the trucks that transported the
detainees, the truck parked outside under the gate -- I mean near
that gate.  The truck did not come into the compound of the
prison.  They parked outside.
Q. Did you notice other activities of the staff at S-21 towards
other detainees?
A. When I was painting at Tuol Sleng, I saw female detainees.
Some pregnant detainees would be walked away while being kicked
by the guards -- female guards.  And they asked them to walk
faster and they walked past Building B and then -- I mean from
south to north, from Building A to B.  I did not know where they
would be detained, but they passed us while we were painting the
portraits.
Q. The last question.  When you left with Uncle Nath and other
survivors from S-21 on the 7th of January 1979, did you notice
that in the buildings of S-21 there were some prisoners left?
A. Mr. President, I think it is more about freedom of the
prisoners.  Prisoners were deprived of their liberty and we would
not be allowed to move, so people -- I think there was quiet
inside.
Q. My question is this.  I mean the last day, the last day when
you left S-21, because there were dead bodies on the beds.  There
were 14 of them.  Some witnesses would say that there were only
10; the accused said that there were only four people; and now
the survivors, including you yourself, have noticed that there
would be some kind of noise and could see people were still left
inside the building during the time when you were leaving the
premises.
The question is whether you could receive any information or see
that detainees still were there on the 17th (sic) of January
1979, the moment before you were leaving S-21.  So just tell us
whether you saw people still there at the premises when you were
leaving.
A. Mr. President, the last day on the 7th of January I left S-21
at about 9 a.m.  We heard the gunshots and we were ordered to
leave immediately.  At that moment I did not see or hear any
noise, and I was so panicked that I did not pay attention to who
would remain, because they pointed the guns at us and they warned
us not to even turn back.  We had to really walk forward
otherwise we would get killed or shot.  So I did not see any one
I guess.

Q. Uncle Meng, when the interrogators stopped torturing you
because you agreed to confess and it was a false confession, was
it based on the purpose in order to satisfy the interrogators, or
you survived because of your skill as a painter?
A. Mr. President, regarding the torture inflicted upon me --
after they still couldn't extract the confession from me because
I gave the same response every day, and because I did not know
who was the leader or who introduced me into the CIA or KGB, they
kept beating me up every day.
And because they could not get my confession, they took me to the
building which is now where you can purchase the ticket to visit
the museum.  I was asked to sit there and they wrote a false
confession and ordered me to sign.  I can not recall the content
of that confession, it's been so many years now, and also because
of the serious torture inflicted upon me my memory was not good.
And at that time, if my memory was like I am now, I would not be
able to paint the portrait and I would not survive because during
that time if they thought somebody lied, especially lying to
Angkar, then that one would be dead.
Q. During the time that they decided to use you as a painter to
paint the portraits of the leaders, including Brother Number 1,
Pol Pot, and other leaders including the Chinese leader as you
stated, what happened during the times that you did the painting?
For instance, were you detained again as a prisoner?
A. Mr. President, no.  During the times that I did the painting I
worked every day regularly so it took me a long time to complete
the four portraits.  That was after I had been tortured.
Q. Until now, can you try to remember or recall, besides the
serious torture inflicted upon you with the present scars on your
back until today, was the situation of receiving torture
physically or emotionally, did it happen elsewhere?
A. Mr. President, if you talk about my memory, I am very
forgetful now.  My memory is not as good as when I was young.
For example, if I leave something somewhere, sometimes I forget
where I left it.

nationality, whether they were European, American or Australian.
They were detained in the same common room as I was detained, and
they had the same food ration as I received.
Q. Were you aware of any foreigners other than westerners or
Vietnamese, such as Thais, people from Thailand?
A. Your Honour, I did not see any Thai citizens.  I only saw
Vietnamese people and some foreigners.  They were tall, they had
bright eyes, and sort of bronze hair.  Besides that I did not see
any other nationality, including Thai.
Q. In addition to the Vietnamese soldiers, whom you saw, did you
see any ordinary Vietnamese people; that is people who were not
soldiers?

soldiers.  And I saw these one civilian, as I said earlier, he
said he knew he was a real artist, but when Duch ordered him to
test, to make the mould and he couldn't do it, and, of course, at
that time Angkar was not happy -- was not happy of anybody lying
to Angkar.  And I don't have anything else to say regarding this
question.
Q. The people whom you think might have been westerners, and the
ordinary Vietnamese people whom you saw, were they all treated
the same way as you were?
A. Your Honour, for the prisoners the treatment was not the same.

I, myself, knew clearly about what happened to me, and I cannot
say about what happened to other inmates.
Q. Did you see many children at S-21?
A. Your Honour, for children at S-21, I did not see any of them
walking around or detained there.  I only saw those children in
the photos, but I did not see them personally during the time of
my detention.  This is my frank and honest response.
Q. Did you ever hear the sounds of children around S-21?
A. Your Honour, for the sound of children, I did not hear.  I
only heard the screaming, asking for help of the adult people
while I was in the common room.  And while I was in the
individual room, individual cell, I also heard the screaming, but
the screaming of the adult, not the children.

BY JUDGE LAVERGNE:
Q. Good afternoon, Mr. Bou Meng.
I also have a few questions to ask you, to try to clarify what
you already explained in detail to the Chamber earlier on today.
I think I understood through what you said this morning, and
through what I have read in your testimony, that your life was
essentially impacted by many sacrifices, and by a life of
obedience.  And you said this morning that you answered Prince
Sihanouk's call in 1970 to free Cambodia, to liberate Cambodia.
Is that so?
A. At that time, I heard the appeal of the Prince Sihanouk on the
radio broadcast.  I was not sure which broadcast was it.  He
appealed for his children to go to the maquis forest to struggle,
so I decided to enter the maquis forest in 1971 with another
friend from K25 office.
So we went to the maquis forest to make some sketches and drawing
of Marx and Lenin.  I was the one who drew the pictures of Marx
and Lenin.  And those sketches were stencilled and distributed to
various units in order to understand the supreme leaders of the
Communists -- of the Communist country.  There were five of them
all together: Karl Marx, Engels, Lenin, Mao Zhedong.  So I even
drew the sketches of these people on the cloth.
Q. So you worked there for the -- at the services of the
Communist Party of Kampuchea's propaganda.  You were very
respectful of what you were requested to do.  And then between
the end of your activity with the propaganda services and your
job at the Orussei Technical School, did you do anything else
between; was there another episode in your career?
A. Your Honour, let me correct that.  It was called the Russei
Keo Technical School, not Orussei Technical School.
Q. Did you go directly from the propaganda services to the Russei
Keo Technical School or did you do anything in between?
A. In between that time -- in order to make it easier to
understand, let me go back. First, I worked for the Ministry of
Commerce, of State Commerce,  and Koy Thuon was the Prime
Minister at the time.  I was requested to draw placards for a
boat.  It was called Marinal Transport.  And I made some other
placards and signs and boards for those boats and vehicles while
I was there.
Q. Well, back then did you trust the CPK entirely?  Were you
somebody who was very much obedient, who would follow what you
were being told to do?
A. Your Honour, that was my specialty, the skills that I had.  I
knew that the evacuation of people from Phnom Penh disappointed
me because I struggled, I was so sick with malaria, and in the
end I received such a suffering which is indescribable.  I felt
so regretful for such inhumane acts of leadership which did not
satisfy my willing -- my understanding.  I physically served them
but emotionally I did not, although I wore black shirt, but my
mind was not black.  I did what I was instructed, based on my
skill.
This is my response, Your Honour.
Q. Was there a specific moment where you might have entirely lost
trust in the CPK?  Was there any moment when you said to yourself
that what you might have believed in did not correspond to
reality?
A. I don't really understand your question.  Can you rephrase
your question again and please try to be simplified and make it
short?
Q. Well, can we say that when you were working for the Russei Keo
School and when you worked previously for the propaganda
services, that you trusted the CPK and Angkar?
A. Your Honour, I carry out the task based on the assignment from
my superior, including drawing the sketches of the machines or
for the new parts of the machines.  Everything was done based on
the instructions from the chairman of that technical school.
This is my response, Your Honour.
Q. You explained that your superiors at the technical school had
been arrested and that you yourself had been sent to be
re-educated.  At that moment, was your trust in the CPK -- was it
-- did it change or did you still have full trust in the CPK?
A. At that time, Your Honour, I lost my trust because my
performance in carrying out the assignment was excellent, I did
what I was asked, but I could not understand why I was
transferred to be re-educated at the Ta Lei Co-operative.  I was
disappointed and this is my frank response to you.  I no longer
had my trust.
Q. But, however, despite the difficult conditions in which you
were, you continued obeying and you continued following the
orders that were given to you.  Is that why it was particularly
difficult for you to understand why you had been arrested by
security cadres of the CPK?
A. Your Honour, at that time, I myself and some other people
totalling about 10, were transferred from the Russei Keo
Technical School to Ta Lei Co-operative and I did not know the
reason for the transfer.
However, before the transfer we were instructed to make our
biography, as I can recall, so I made my biography to the Angkar
and about one or two months later I was transferred to the Ta Lei
Co-operative amongst about 10 other people, including my wife.
So we were tempered to do hard labour at the Ta Lei Co-operative.
I did not know the reason for the transfer, Your Honour.
Q. Back then, had you heard of the security centres?  Were you
aware, for example, of the existence of S-21 or of other security
centres?
A. Your Honour, regarding the security offices or the prisons, I
did not hear anything at all during the time, however, people
kept disappearing.  Some probably were sent for re-education or
sent for training here and there.
I had heard a lot about transferring of people or relocation of
people starting from 1976, and I was wondering how come, while
people were still working good and they were transferred
elsewhere?  Or whether they had any plan of transforming in the
agriculture production?  I only had doubt in my mind, however, I
just kept doing what I was given or instructed.
So I typed some documents that I was asked to do and I drew
sketches for the students to study.  I could not understand their
thinking.  They were in a higher class and I thought I belonged
to the lower class with limited technical capability.
Q. Can we say that you were not at all aware of having committed
any kind of offence that you absolutely were not aware having
betrayed the CPK, that you had absolutely no awareness of being
part of a group of traitors?
A. When I came I knew that there was a Minister of Propaganda,
Mr. Ho Nim, who
called me to draw a portrait of the embarkment structure.  And at
that time the current king was teaching students how to perform
the ballet dancing and then he told me to help draw a portrait of
his father.  And he called his father the normal, ordinary
person's language and I was surprised but I did not ask further
questions.
Probably they saw the picture, the photo that the king asked me
to draw; that's why they arrested me, or not.  I'm not quite
sure.
Q. This morning, you also talked, at length, about the
ill-treatment that was inflicted upon you.  You also talked about
the physiological consequences thereof.  You also said to us that
you still had scars.  I seem to have understood that these
tortures led to other consequences, such as problems with your
hearing.  Do you have other physiological conditions or
difficulties that you may ascribe to being the consequences of
that ill-treatment?
A. I was slapped and I was beaten on the head; all kinds of
tortures had been inflicted on me.  So in short, I believe that
because I was severely tortured, that I look older than my age
and I lose all the teeth, and I can observe that Brother Chum Mey
still have his teeth.  And also I have had problems with hearing
and I think this is probably the consequence of the torture.  And
I look much older than I am and if you compare to the age, I
think I should have not been that old if I was not tortured.
Q. From what you can remember, do you have the feeling that the
people interrogating you were enjoying themselves by making you
suffer or seeing you suffer?
A. During the time when I was being interrogated some people ate
the jackfruit and they threw the remaining -- the peel of the
jackfruit onto my head and I could feel like then I was perceived
as enemy and prisoner.  I could not do anything but to let them
do whatever they wish and they did not show any mercy towards me
as a human being.  And whenever I recall it, I cannot hold back
my tears.  I was so disappointed that I had devoted myself for
the work and after all I end up being tortured.  I wished I were
killed by the malaria in the jungle, but I think my life was
valuable that I could survive longer to be tortured again.
That's all, Your Honour.
Q. When you were a painter at the workshop, do you now remember
having been taken out of the workshop in relation to an incident?
You were taken away from the workshop for about two weeks; do you
remember that?  Do you remember then coming back to the workshop,
having to say you were sorry, seek forgiveness?  Do you remember
having been kicked?  Do you remember this episode or something
like this, or do you not remember something like this happening
to you?
A. I think, through my recollection, this incident might not have
happened.  I knew that one of my neighbours in my next room was
taken away -- no, the guy who worked next to my school -- the
technical school of Russei Keo.  A couple were taken or arrested.
I don't know whether two of them or one of them was arrested but
they both disappeared.  Then it came my turn who were transferred
to Ta Lei Co-operative and that's what I have seen and known and
I think my memory is not that good.  Maybe I have not fully
recollected all the episodes, and accept my apologies for not
being able to recall everything.  That's all.
Q. Mr. Bou Meng, sorry, I was referring to the period when you
were working in the workshop at S-21.  You were at the workshop
in S-21.  During that period when you were working at S-21
workshop, where you were working with Vann Nath and other
artists; during that period, was there an episode the result of
which was that you had to go and say sorry; that you had to go
and apologize?
A. I don't know whether the apologies were made to my colleagues
or to the guards.  I'm not quite sure I understand the question.
Q. Were you forced to apologize to your colleagues in the
workshop at S-21 or to other people?  Were you, one day, shackled
or tied up and led to go and offer apologies to either your
colleagues or somebody else in the workshop?
A. I cannot recall or maybe I forgot, because I never offered my
apologies to anyone, even to my colleagues.  It is based on my
recollection but of course I would have forgotten.  As the Khmer
proverb says, "The elephants with four legs would have collapsed
sometime and the wise person would forget anyway."
Q. Thank you, Mr. Bou Meng, for these responses.  I have one very
last question for you.
This morning you told us that the accused had talked about
fertilizer, saying that humans could be fertilizer in the paddy
fields.  Could you explain to us the meaning of this term,
please?
A.  The statement is based on the accused Kaing Guek Eav, alias
Duch.  He said that if I could not resemble the portrait of Pol
Pot then I would be used as the human fertilizer.
And I didn't understand whether I would be used to produce
fertilizer or would I be used as the fertilizer myself for the
rice field.  That's what he asked me and I found it difficult to
respond to him also at that moment.
Q. Thank you very much, Mr. Bou Meng.

I have no further questions, Mr. President.

hospital specializing in hearing and then they offered me a

listen to people talking I would not be able to listen or to
understand their conversation unless I paid very close attention,
or move very close to them.  So if I could put number one to 10,
I could hear about 30 percent.  I mean three out of 10 because of
my impairment.  And I think my eyesight were not good.  My teeth,

Of course, when people get old, this kind of thing will get old

older than my age because I had been tortured, otherwise I would
be ok now.  And my ears would have not been that bad.  So here --

there.
Q.   Thank you.  My next question.
I want to know about your suffering.  How long had you endured
this suffering or you still feel the suffering at the present
time?
A. Are you talking about the suffering, the physical suffering,
in addition to the emotional suffering?
Q. Thank you.  I meant regarding your earache.  So you suffered
when they tortured you.  Are your ears in a better condition now?
A. They are fully recovered, however, I have had hard hearing.
So that's why I need the hearing aid so that I could hear
properly.  Without the hearing aid, I could hardly hear anything.
That's all.
Q. Thank you.  Regarding the electrocution, as you stated that
they used the wall power outlet to electrocute you.  You said you

electrocuted, I fell unconscious immediately, and when I gained
my consciousness, the water was everywhere on my face.
Q. Thank you.  Did they place the wire on your pants or on your
flesh directly?
A.  It was placed on my shorts, however, there was a machine that
I think it controlled the voltage, and that machine hooked into
the power outlet from the wall.  So I think they could increase
the voltage from that machine.
But you could easily understand that if the voltage was not
strong enough, then I would not fall unconscious.  That's it.
Q. Thank you.  You already informed the Chamber that once you
were electrocuted, you fell unconscious straight away.  And for
how long did you become unconscious?
A. If you are unconscious, it's like you were sleeping.  You
would not know how long you fell unconscious.
Q. On another matter, did you go and make consultation with the
psychological support?
A. Previously, I have had consultation with a psychological
support.  I was assisted with some tablets so that I would not
have insomnia, and I take two types of tablets on a daily basis.
But when I come to the Court and speak in this current condition,
I can't not even eat my lunch today because I was overwhelmed and
I did not feel like eating anything.

Peng and Kuy, but you haven't clearly verified that for each
interrogation, were the five present and beating you up or were
you interrogated and tortured by only one interrogator at a time?
A.   They were there during the interrogation, but only one
person beat me at a time and then they took turns.  First Chan
beat me up.  He asked me to count the number of lashes.  When I
counted up to 10 I told him, and he said, "It's not yet 10, I
only hit you once".  And I can remember his word.  I remember his
words, I remember his face.
I can always remember his face, the person who mistreated me.  I
remember both, those who did good thing and who did bad things to
me.
Q. Thank you.  The question is, on one day during the
interrogation, were the five interrogators beat you up on that
same day or only they came on another day?
A. That group of interrogators, the five of them, they took turns
to beat me up until all the five became exhausted or when the
time was up.  For example, from 7 a.m. until about 11 or 12, then
they rested.  I saw all of them.
Q. So from what I can understand, you confirmed that in -- for
each date, the five of them present at the same time.  Is that
true?
A. That is correct.
Q. My next question.  You stated to the Chamber that when they
water-hosed you in the common room, so all the inmates had to
take off their clothes, and later on they had to dry the floor
with their shorts.
The question is, did the guards order the prisoners to take off

then we were scattered and I walked across National Road Number
4.
Q. Thank you.  I just want to know when you left, you left along
with Chum Mey and Vann Nath.
And my next question is I just want the confirmation.  This
morning you said when you fled S-21, one time you said it was at
6 p.m. and the other time you said at 9 a.m.  And when Ty Srinna
asked you, you said you went at about 6 or 7 p.m.  So can you
tell me exactly what time you left S-21?
A. Mr. Defence Counsel, I left Tuol Sleng prison at 9 o'clock.
We left the painting workshop and we were ordered to walk
straight in one line.  We were so fearful, so we walked in one
line and when we reached a house we stopped and stayed there for
quite a while.  I cannot recall the location.  Maybe it's the
Beehive radio station.
Q. I just want to know the time.  So you say now it's at 9
o'clock in the morning.
And my seventh question, which is the last question; when you
were painting the portrait did you ever see Khieu Samphan coming
to visit?
A. Mr. Defence Counsel, I never saw Khieu Samphan come in.  All
those senior peoples, I never saw them.  Even Pol Pot, I only saw
his photo; I never saw him in person.  Sometimes people ask
whether I saw Pol Pot personally because I painted his portrait.
In fact I never saw him in person.  I also had my portrait
painted for a Chinese shop in Shanghai.
Q. Thank you.  So when you painted the portrait at the technical
school did Khieu Samphan ever go there?
A. Mr. Defence Counsel, I can recall when you ask me that
question because I worked there.  At that time I was preparing
the numbers of the pages and Mr. Khieu Samphan asked me, "Do you
have a telephone?" and then I told him and I pointed -- oh, the
telephone was at the corner, because I didn't know that he was
Khieu Samphan.  But when he left, my work colleague told me that,
"That was Khieu Samphan," and I felt rather surprised.  So now I
can recall.
Q. Thank you.

Q. Good evening, Mr. Bou Meng.  Judge Lavergne brought up earlier
on the fact that when you were working in the CPK propaganda
service, which was at the Russei Keo, you were somebody who was
very obedient.  And if I've understood correctly, you indicated
that you followed along physically but not emotionally.  Could
you please develop this assertion, this idea?
A. Ms. Defence Counsel, the work that was assigned to me by Hak
to draw sketches of the machines, of the half a machine or of the
new spare parts, or the sketches of vehicle machines, all types
of machinery, I drew all those sketches to include in the book
for the students to study at that time.
My recollection in making that document for those technical
school participants, that was what I did.  Of course I obeyed the
order from the upper echelon and my superior, Hak, assigned me to
make or compile those documents.  That is all my answer.
Q. Could you please tell us why emotionally you said that you
didn't follow along?  I understood that you were just obeying to
an order, so therefore of course you were obeying physically, we
could say, but why do you state that you did not obey
emotionally?
A. On this matter let me tell you, Ms. Defence Counsel,
physically I followed the assignment and, as my skill was in
drawing sketches, I just did it.  But in my mind I did not have
100 percent confidence and trust in the leadership, and the
reason?  Because I saw people being evacuated from the city, and
the city became like a ghost city.  And this is my response to
you.
Q. This will be my last question.  So why, therefore, did you
continue obeying physically?
A. Ms. Defence Counsel, regarding my assignment as a painter or a
sketch drawer, I had to do it.  I had to carry out my task and
even if I completed and carried out my task 100 percent, I was
still being transferred.
So I was transferred to the Ta Lei Co-operative and that act made
me lost my trust in that regime.
Q. Given the answer, would you please give me the leave for
another question?  Therefore, could I understand that it was
because you were afraid that you continued obeying physically?
A. I don't really understand your question.  Can you ask the
question again?
Q. You are telling us that if you did not follow the orders 100
percent that were given to you that you could be transferred.  So
therefore can I conclude from this answer that it was fear that
made you follow 100 percent the orders that were given to you?
A. In fact, that was the case.
